    pearls: ["Knee-chest position is the FIRST nursing action during a Tet spell  -  it increases systemic vascular resistance, which reduces right-to-left shunting and forces blood through the pulmonary valve", "Squatting in older, unrepaired children is the self-taught equivalent of knee-chest  -  children instinctively assume this position to relieve cyanosis", "Boot-shaped heart on CXR is classic: concavity at the pulmonary artery segment with upturned apex from RV hypertrophy", "Do NOT administer digoxin during Tet spells  -  increased contractility worsens infundibular obstruction"],
    quiz: [{ question: "A 4-month-old with known Tetralogy of Fallot suddenly becomes deeply cyanotic, irritable, and is breathing rapidly. What is the FIRST nursing action?", options: ["Administer 100% oxygen via face mask", "Place the infant in knee-chest position", "Administer IV morphine as ordered", "Prepare for emergent intubation"], correct: 1, rationale: "Knee-chest position is the immediate first action during a Tet spell. It increases systemic vascular resistance (SVR) by compressing the femoral arteries, which reduces right-to-left shunting across the VSD and redirects more blood through the stenotic pulmonary valve to the lungs. Oxygen, morphine, and other interventions follow but positioning comes first." }]
